attributes.title: The clinical utility of a syndrome conceptualization of moral injury

q1.value: The clinical utility of a syndrome conceptualization of moral injury

q2.value: Stephanie A. Houle, Andrea R. Ashbaugh

q3.value: The purpose of this study is to examine the clinical utility of moral injury, a proposed syndrome describing the psychological consequences of experiencing events that transgress deeply held moral beliefs and values. Such consequences include pervasive guilt and shame, existential distress, and disruptions in identity and spirituality (Litz et al., 2009; Farnsworth et al., 2017; Griffin et al., 2019; Jinkerson, 2016). To date, this construct has been studied primarily in the military context, and debate is ongoing as to whether the psychological consequences of events that seriously challenge one’s moral beliefs are captured by other diagnostic entities, such as posttraumatic stress disorder, or if moral injury warrants attention as a distinct syndrome. In this study, three related research questions will be examined: 1) How are cases of moral injury currently being diagnosed and treated? 2) Is the conceptualization of moral injury as a syndrome perceived by clinicians as being clinically useful? and 3) How acceptable is the moral injury syndrome conceptualization to clinicians?

q4.value:
This study is exploratory in nature. While research suggests that clinicians find moral injury (MI) to be a clinically useful construct (Drescher et al., 2011), there remains significant contention as to whether or not the phenomenology of MI falls within the purview of existing diagnostic entities (e.g., PTSD). Further, the MI construct has mostly been studied in the United States, and little is known about the impact of potentially morally injurious experiences among Canadian Forces personnel and veterans, and thus the phenomenology of MI in the Canadian military context.


This study aims to answer three questions: 1) How are cases of moral injury currently being diagnosed and treated? 2) Is the conceptualization of moral injury as a syndrome perceived by clinicians as being clinically useful? and 3) How acceptable is the moral injury syndrome conceptualization to clinicians?


Question 1: This question can only be answered by providing descriptive data, and no specific hypothesis has been generated for this question. 


Question 2: Two groups of participants will be compared – one group will be exposed to the MI symptom profile developed for this study, and one group will not. We expect that exposure to the MI symptom profile will increase diagnostic reliability for the clinical vignette representing MI symptomatology. This would indicate that exposure to the MI syndrome description improved agreement with regards to diagnostic decision making for cases of MI.


Question 3: This question can only be answered by providing descriptive data, and no specific hypothesis has been generated for this question.

q5.value: Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized controlled trials.

value: For studies that involve human subjects, they will not know the treatment group to which they have been assigned.

question.value:
Question 1 will be answered using descriptive information obtained by the group of participants not exposed to the MI symptom profile.

Question 2 will be answered using a between-subjects analysis, with the independent variable being exposure or not to criteria for the moral injury syndrome. All participants will view three clinical vignettes – one encompassing criteria for posttraumatic stress disorder (PTSD), one encompassing criteria for major depressive disorder (MDD), and one encompassing criteria for moral injury (MI). Each vignette includes a trauma scenario that was designed to include elements of moral challenges, as well as life threat (so as to meet DSM-5 criterion A for a traumatic event). The traumatic event description and diagnostic criteria will be counterbalanced across participants (e.g., creating 9 possible vignettes) and presented at random. Each participant will view 1 PTSD vignette, 1 MDD vignette, and 1 MI vignette.

Question 3 will be answered using descriptive information. In those exposed to the MI symptom profile, the proportion of participants that choose Moral Injury as the most likely diagnosis for a vignette (regardless of accuracy) will be reported. This will give an indication as to how acceptable moral injury is as a diagnostic construct (i.e., how willing participants are to apply the construct, regardless if they do it accurately). Participants in both groups will also be asked explicitly about their perceptions of the utility of the construct, and their willingness to apply it. Responses to these questions will be reported as descriptive data.

q10.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value:
Participants will be registered clinicians who will be recruited online by three means. First, electronic communications (e.g., e-mails, posts on social media or other forums) with a recruitment message for the study will be disseminated by professional psychology and related organizations in Canada (e.g., the Canadian Psychological Association, the Ontario Psychological Association, the Canadian Psychiatric Association). Second, in order to ensure adequate representation of clinicians with exposure to military clients, we will approach government-affiliated networks of clinics serving Canadian Forces personnel and veterans, who specialize in the treatment of operational stress injuries to disseminate the survey, using the same recruitment message. Third, a snowball-sampling method will be applied, whereby clinicians invited to participate in the survey will be asked to disseminate the survey to their professional colleagues. 

Three clinical vignettes have been developed for this study, representing symptomatology consistent with the diagnoses of PTSD, major depressive disorder (using DSM-5 criteria), and moral injury. All vignettes first describe a potentially traumatic event, which include both features of trauma (as defined by criterion A of PTSD in the DSM-5) and of a moral transgression, as defined above. Event and syndrome descriptions will be counterbalanced across participants, such that 9 possible vignettes are created (e.g., Event 1 + PTSD, Event 1 + MDD, Event 1 + MI, Event 2 + PTSD, and so on). This is to control for the potential impact of the event description on the participants' diagnostic impression of the patient in the vignette. Only one correct diagnosis is possible for each vignette (e.g., PTSD for the PTSD vignette). 

The study survey will be available online through the survey platform Qualtrics. Participants who click on the survey link in the recruitment message will be randomly assigned to one of two groups: Half of participants will be provided with a description of the MI syndrome before viewing clinical vignettes (MI group) and half will be exposed to the syndrome description only after having completed the vignette survey (No-MI group). All participants will be provided with the same study material, the only difference being the order.

Upon opening the survey, all participants will first be asked to provide consent.

MI group procedure: 
Participants will first be shown a description of the MI syndrome developed for this study. Participants will then be presented with the three clinical vignettes, in random order, and be asked to provide their most likely diagnosis and treatment approach for each vignette. Participants in this group will have the option to select Moral Injury as a diagnosis. 

If participants select PTSD, MDD, or MI as a diagnosis, they will also be asked to highlight which criteria of these disorders are present in the vignette. This will provide an indication as to what elements of each disorder is being identified as such in each of the vignettes. MI group participants will then complete questions on the perceived utility of the MI syndrome description and demographic information.

No-MI group procedure:
Participants in this group will commence the study by reading the three clinical vignettes and providing their most likely diagnosis and treatment approach for each. They will not have the option of selecting Moral Injury as a diagnosis. If participants select PTSD or MDD as diagnoses, they will be asked to identify which criteria of these disorders are present in the vignette. After this section, participants will be presented with the MI syndrome description, and will then complete questions on the perceived utility of the MI syndrome description and demographic information.

Once the survey is complete, participants will be thanked for their participation and provided with a debriefing form, which outlines the purpose of the research and presents relevant, and compensated for their time.

q13.value: Our target sample size is 120. We will attempt to collect up to 200 participants, assuming that not all will provide complete data.

q14.value: A power analysis using G*Power 3.1.9.2 (Faul et al., 2007) was conducted for the planned statistical analysis for Question 2 (goodness of fit test). For this between-participant analysis, the study would require a total of 108 participants to achieve .80 power in detecting a small- to medium-sized interaction (w = .30) with a .05 alpha. A sample size of 120 would therefore be ideal to ensure adequate power.

question.value: Participants will be randomly assigned to one of two conditions differentiated by exposure (MI-group) or not (No-MI group) to the MI symptom profile prior to viewing a set of standardized clinical vignettes. Those in the MI-group will have the option of selecting Moral Injury as a diagnosis for any given vignette, and those in the No-MI group will not have this option.

The main variables related to the research questions are:

Question 1 – Diagnosis and treatment options chosen for each clinical vignette (No-MI group only).

Question 2 – Proportion of correct and incorrect diagnoses for each clinical vignette.

Question 3 – Responses on questions pertaining to the acceptability and utility of the MI symptom profile.

Question 1: How are cases of moral injury currently being diagnosed and treated?

To examine this question, responses from the No-MI group as to their diagnosis and treatment options for each vignette will be reported as descriptive data. Given that the No-MI group of participants will not have had exposure to the MI syndrome description beforehand, and will be prompted to apply only DSM-5 diagnostic criteria, descriptive data will give an indication as to how cases of MI are currently being diagnosed and treated by clinicians. 

Question 2: Is the conceptualization of moral injury as a syndrome clinically useful?

Diagnostic and treatment decisions will be recorded for each group. For each vignette, participants will be given a score of 1 if they selected the correct diagnosis for the vignette, and a score of 0 if they selected the incorrect diagnosis for that vignette. For those in the No-MI group who do not have access to the MI syndrome beforehand, the correct diagnosis for the MI vignette based on current DSM-5 criteria is Other Specified Trauma and Related Disorder. For those in the MI-group, the correct diagnosis for the MI vignette is Moral Injury. Based on this scoring, we will conduct a goodness of fit test to examine differences in the proportion of correct diagnoses for each vignette in the MI-group vs. the No MI group. We expect that there will be no statistically significant differences between correct responses for the PTSD and MDD vignettes, but that comparisons will be significantly different for the MI vignette. This would indicate that exposure to the MI syndrome description improved agreement with regards to diagnostic decision making for cases of MI.

Question 3: How acceptable is the moral injury syndrome conceptualization to clinicians? 

In the MI group, the proportion of participants that choose Moral Injury as the most likely diagnosis for a vignette (regardless of accuracy) will be reported. This will give an indication as to how acceptable moral injury is as a diagnostic construct (i.e., how willing participants are to apply the construct, regardless if they do it accurately). Participants in both groups will also be asked explicitly about their perceptions of the utility of the construct, and their willingness to apply it. Responses to these questions will be reported as descriptive data.

q21.value: We will use the standard p<.05 criteria to determine if the goodness of fit test for Question 2 is statistically significant. We will also present and interpret effect size for this test.

q24.value: Differences in diagnostic accuracy may be examined based on different demographic criteria, such as profession (e.g, psychologist, psychiatrist) or previous training and experience with military members and veterans.

attributes.title: Post-operative Respiratory failure in Cardiothoracic surgery patients: A Scoping review

q1.value: Post-operative Respiratory failure in Cardiothoracic Surgery patients: A Scoping Review

q3.value: Post-operative respiratory failure (PRF) is defined as ventilator dependency for over 48 hours or unplanned reintubation within 30 days. It is a frequent complication in cardiac surgery and is associated with significant morbidity and mortality. in this scoping review, we intend to find out what is already out there on this subject.

q4.value: We hypothesize that the scoping review will reveal a gap in medical literature available on Post-operative Respiratory failure in Cardiothoracic Surgery patients.

value: No blinding is involved in this study.

question.value: It is a scoping review. We intend to establish a comprehensive search of the database to find literature on Respiratory failure in Cardiothoracic surgery patients. the initial wide search will be based on the keywords. This search will be further narrowed down to fewer articles that meet the inclusion criteria. We will review the articles and publish the manuscript. All information will be documented.

q10.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value: Data collection will involve the documentation of all resources used, all identified articles that are selected through the title/abstract and full-text screening phases.

q13.value: It will depend on the number of articles in the medical literature that meet our inclusion criteria.

question.value: It is a scoping review to identify all the available literature on post-operative respiratory failure in cardiothoracic surgery patients.
No statistical tests as this will be a narrative analysis.

attributes.title: Sex differences in misperceptions of sexual interest can be explained by sociosexual orientation and men projecting their own interest onto women.
attributes.description: Sex differences in misperceptions of sexual interest have been well documented; however, it is unclear whether this cognitive bias could be explained by other factors. In the current study, 1226 participants (578 men, 630 women) participated in a speed-dating study, where participants rated their sexual interest in each other as well as the sexual interest they perceived from their partners. Consistent with previous findings, we found that men tended to overperceive sexual interest from their partners, while women tended to underperceive sexual interest. However, this sex difference becomes negligible when considering potential mediators, such as the raters’ sociosexual orientation, and raters projecting their own levels of sexual interest onto their partners. These findings challenge the popular notion that sex differences in misperceptions in sexual interest have evolved as a specialised adaptation due to different selection pressures in men and women.

attributes.title: Nasal Microbiome of Medical Students UdeC
attributes.description: Nasal bacterial and fungal microbiome of medical students

summary.value: This registration contains the files that show the OTU's list of the bacterial and fungal microbiome obtained from the nose of medical students with a known long-term Staphylococcus aureus nasal carrier status. It also contains a spreadsheet that details the results for all participants in the study, including MRSA/MSSA results and carrier classification, highlighting the subset of participants that were included in the microbiome analysis
